The Pythagorean Theorem for vectors states that $||\mathbf{u}||^2 + ||\mathbf{v}||^2 = ||\mathbf{u} + \mathbf{v}||^2$ if and only if $\mathbf{u}$ and $\mathbf{v}$ are orthogonal (i.e., $\mathbf{u} \cdot \mathbf{v} = 0$). If $\mathbf{u}$ and $\mathbf{v}$ are NOT orthogonal, then $\mathbf{u} \cdot \mathbf{v} 
eq 0$. Since $||\mathbf{u} + \mathbf{v}||^2 = ||\mathbf{u}||^2 + 2(\mathbf{u} \cdot \mathbf{v}) + ||\mathbf{v}||^2$, if $\mathbf{u} \cdot \mathbf{v} 
eq 0$, then $||\mathbf{u} + \mathbf{v}||^2 
eq ||\mathbf{u}||^2 + ||\mathbf{v}||^2$. Therefore, option B is generally true.
